faq-body=<div class="section"><h2>Brand new to Golbin?</h2><p>Welcome!</p><p>Golbin is the popular publishing platform and community that makes it easy for you to create &quot;stories&quot; online. Stories are pages, kind of like flyers or signposts or overview articles, that gather everything you know about your topic of interest--and snap it all into focus. Like the story of a camera, your perspective on something. (You're looking at a story right now).</p><p>It's a super-simple, fun and powerful way to share your interests, build your online identity and credibility, and connect with new readers and friends. It's all free, and you could even earn money for yourself.</p><p>Because there's so much you can DO with Golbin, we know it can get a little overwhelming when you're brand new and still poking around. So many different ways to make a page, different themes and colors and ... what was that about money?</p><p>So, while there's a ton more to know (and you'll figure it out over time, never fear) we wanted to put together this overview page for you. It's got some vocabulary, some examples, and a basic lowdown on what you can expect from Golbin. If you look at the tabs up top, you'll see there's a lot more info here too, like our Terms of Service, a FAQ and more. No need to read it all, but good to reference back to over time.</p><p>I hope you'll feel comfortable poking around and exploring, and when you're ready, try making a &quot;story&quot; of your own.</p><p>Thanks for visiting.</p></div><div class="section"><h2>What kinds of stories can you make?</h2><h3>All kinds. Every kind.</h3><p>Not sure what you can make a story about? You could make an About Me story (well, about you). Or a review story. Or a story about your blog, to help point traffic to it. Or a story about your art. Or your eBay or Etsy or Zazzle or CafePress shop. Or about your hobby. Or your dogs. Or your hometown. Or your favorite books or movies or video games.</p><p>Here are a few more places to get ideas, and a few tips for getting started:</p></div><div class="section"><h2>What's this about money? A real world example.</h2><h3>and how does that work?</h3><a class="right" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/hollyclark/596587085/" title="Cupcakes are fun to make. by OrangeCounty_Girl, on Flickr"><img src="http://farm2.staticflickr.com/1093/596587085_ac515f7aa8.jpg" width="236" height="250" alt="Cupcakes are fun to make."></a><b>Let's look at a example scenario.</b><p>Robin is a very busy, very creative woman. She was helping plan her son's wedding and put together "this story all about the mother-son dance songs" they were considering, and then asked her friends to comment on their favorites. She added YouTube music videos of some of the songs, a list of her top contenders, an open comments section for other moms to post the songs they danced to with their sons.</p><p>So now, if you land on her story and you like one of the contextual Google ads we've matched to her page and you either buy or click, Robin earns money. (This page was entirely free for her to make, remember).</p><p>She's also made about 300 other stories on things like "Best Panini Sandwich Recipes" and "Bunches of Cute Birthday Cupcakes".</p><p>In fact, Robin has gotten so good at making recommendation stories about the stuff she knows and loves that she's one of our very top earners, making thousands of dollars on Golbin.</p><p>So that's how it works. Cool, huh?</p><p></div>
